
get_test_wiki_pages.py fetches random wikipedia articles from October 2022 or before, which cannot be AI generated. It also fetches random articles from Category:Articles containing suspected AI-generated texts. It dumps a list of those articles into two CSVs, and then outputs a cleaned version of the prose of those articles to folders in data/.

run_pangram.py runs the articles in data/ through Pangram, an AI detection tool.

data/ contains the confirmed human Wikipedia articles in random_2022/, the suspected AI articles in random_AI_suspected, and AI generated articles I have generated (and thus can confirm are AI) in claude/, gemini/, and gpt/, according to which LLM was used to generate them. The prompt I used was "Write a wikipedia article about [title]. Do not copy the existing wikipedia article or use it as a source." In all cases, the model used was the publically available default free model in the chat interface of the given LLM, and I've turned off history ("incognito mode"/"temporary chat"). I have not copied any clear communication intended for the user (e.g. "Using non-Wikipedia sources, here's the article:") and in some cases did some very minor formatting tweaks. I used the default model (Gemini Flash 3.6, Claude Sonnet 5, and tried to use GPT-5.5 Instant but that didn't exist, so I priced matched approximately to the other models)

pangram_results.csv contains the Pangram evaluations for the articles.

This is very vibe coded. I've been sanity-checking it and verifying the outputs but code is almost entirely Claude Sonnet 5.
